############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "parserCheckboxList.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context('Numeric'); loadMacros( "parserCheckboxList.pl", );
$checks = CheckboxList( [ [ '\(x = ay-b\) for nonzero real numbers \(a,b\)', '\(y = \sqrt{4-x^2}\)', '\(x=e^{y-1}-8\)', '\(x^2 + y^2 = r\) for \(r>0\)' ], 'None of the above' ], [ '\(x = ay-b\) for nonzero real numbers \(a,b\)', '\(y = \sqrt{4-x^2}\)', '\(x=e^{y-1}-8\)' ], labels => "ABC", displayLabels => 1 );
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Determine which of the following equations represent functions on their implied domains. Assume [`x`] is the input variable, and [`y`] is the output variable.
[_]{$checks}{5}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION [`x=ay-b`] can be rearranged as [`y = \frac{1}{a}x + \frac{b}{a}\text{.}`] Since [`a\ne 0\text{,}`] this is simply a line, which is a function.
[`y = \sqrt{4-x^2}`] is already written in functional form. It can be seen that a single value for [`x`] with [`-2\leq x \leq 2`] will yield a single output value [`y\text{.}`] Graphically, this is the top half of a circle.
Solving [`x^2 + y^2 = r`] for [`y`] yields [`y = \pm \sqrt{r-x^2}\text{.}`] This is not a function. For example, [`x=0`] would give [`y = \sqrt{r}`] or [`-\sqrt{r}\text{.}`] Graphically, this is a circle with radius [`\sqrt{r}\text{.}`]
[`x = e^{y-1}-8`] can be rearranged as [`y = \ln(x+8) + 1\text{.}`] This is a logarithmic function.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
